Certainly! Below is a complete HTML file that generates a random function of the form \( Aa^4 + Bb^3 + Cc^2 + Dd \) and displays its graph using the Chart.js library. The file includes embedded CSS and JavaScript, making it a standalone web app.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Function Graph</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        canvas {
            margin-top: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Graph of Random Function</h1>
    <p id="functionEquation"></p>
    <canvas id="functionChart" width="600" height="400"></canvas>

    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
    <script>
        // Generate random coefficients for the function
        const A = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);
        const B = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);
        const C = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);
        const D = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10);

        // Define the function to plot
        const func = (x) => A * Math.pow(x, 4) + B * Math.pow(x, 3) + C * Math.pow(x, 2) + D * x;

        // Generate data points
        const xValues = Array.from({length: 100}, (_, i) => i - 50); // From -50 to 49
        const yValues = xValues.map(func);

        // Display the function equation
        document.getElementById('functionEquation').innerText = `f(x) = ${A}x^4 + ${B}x^3 + ${C}x^2 + ${D}x`;

        // Create the chart
        const ctx = document.getElementById('functionChart').getContext('2d');
        const functionChart = new Chart(ctx, {
            type: 'line',
            data: {
                labels: xValues,
                datasets: [{
                    label: 'f(x)',
                    data: yValues,
                    borderColor: 'rgba(75, 192, 192, 1)',
                    backgroundColor: 'rgba(75, 192, 192, 0.2)',
                    borderWidth: 2,
                    fill: true
                }]
            },
            options: {
                scales: {
                    x: {
                        title: {
                            display: true,
                            text: 'x'
                        }
                    },
                    y: {
                        title: {
                            display: true,
                            text: 'f(x)'
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The file includes a heading, a paragraph to display the function equation, and a canvas element where the graph will be drawn.
- **CSS Styles**: Basic styles to center the content and give the canvas a border.
- **JavaScript**:
  - Generates random coefficients for a polynomial function.
  - Defines the function \( f(x) = Aa^4 + Bb^3 + Cc^2 + Dd \).
  - Creates an array of `x` values ranging from -50 to 49.
  - Computes the corresponding `y` values for each `x`.
  - Displays the function equation on the web page.
  - Uses Chart.js to render the function graph on the canvas.

You can copy the above code into an `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the graph of the randomly generated polynomial function.
